Hi Julian,

         My forthcoming position document on the work I want to perform 
over the next few years has a lot of relevance to modularity.  It is not 
specifically about NEAT, because it is about adding a set of desirable 
features to any evolving software system.  NEAT is one of the systems I 
have had in mind throughout the writing, however.

         I was hoping to have it done by Christmas, but I probably won&#39;t 
make that now.  It won&#39;t be too deep into the new year, however.  And this 
list will be one of the very first places I bring it looking for comments 
and oppinions...

         Ian

At 00:58 06/12/2004, you wrote:

&gt;Hi Joseph,
&gt;
&gt;Thans for pointing to your thesis, which I have now read. Good stuff.
&gt;It did clear up most of the details I was wondering about, but it
&gt;would be handy to have your code available to look at in case there is
&gt;something more I&#39;m wondering about.
&gt;
&gt;I am currently working on comparing different ways of encoding
&gt;modularity for evolving controllers in the simple game of Cellz, where
&gt;agents have radial symmetry. One of the methods will be something very
&gt;much like modular neat, but without the speciation and symbiotic
&gt;coevolution parts. (If I understand your thesis right, you didn&#39;t find
&gt;any evidence that the symbotic coevolution part actually improved
&gt;effectiveness.)
&gt;
&gt;I definitely think that the general idea of modular neat is a (the?)
&gt;key to scaling up evolutionary computation in certain domains with
&gt;inherent symmetry, such as complex visual input. Actually, I&#39;m not
&gt;convinced that artificially embryogenetic systems (e g GRN-based)
&gt;neccessarily have more to offer in terms of evolvability (though they
&gt;might be more interesting from a biological point of view) than the
&gt;straightforward approach to modularity taken in neat.
&gt;
&gt;Julian
&gt;
&gt;On Thu, 2 Dec 2004 14:14:52 -0600 (CST), Joseph Reisinger
&gt;&lt;joeraii@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt;  Hi Julian,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;  I wrote Modular NEAT for my undergraduate thesis at UT; so, the GECCO
&gt; &gt;  paper was kind of a distillation of the thesis, with a little extra work
&gt; &gt;  on measuring modularization. If you&#39;re interested, I put the thesis itself
&gt; &gt;  is in the files section of this group (honors-thesis.ps.gz). That version
&gt; &gt;  is a little heavier on the implementation and analysis side, so it might
&gt; &gt;  be helpful to you.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;  Unfortunately I haven&#39;t put any work into it since finishing the GECCO
&gt; &gt;  paper, though I am working on a GRN-based system that I hope to get some
&gt; &gt;  results on by the next GECCO deadline. Anyway I still have a ton of ideas
&gt; &gt;  for modular NEAT, and I&#39;d love to see the work continue on it. I think the
&gt; &gt;  results were pretty clear that its a powerful optimization, at least for
&gt; &gt;  some types of domains.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;  As for the source code, I&#39;ve been planning for a while now to make a
&gt; &gt;  formal release of it, but I really haven&#39;t had a lot of time to go over
